1148","Abt. 1138":"about 1138","1120":"1120","1085":"1085","Aft. 1120":"after 1120","1095":"1095","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from either of two places called Harley (Shropshire, Yorkshire). The Shropshire placename derives from Old English <i>hær</i> ‘rock, heap of stones’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The Yorkshire placename derives from Old English <i>hara</i> ‘hare’ or <i>hær</i> + <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’, later replaced by <i>lēah</i>.","Irish (Donegal): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarghaile</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earghal</i>’, a variant of the personal name <i>Fearghal</i> without the initial <i>F-</i>. This name has also become   Herley   and   Hurley  . Compare   Arrell   and   Harrell  .","Scottish (Fife): habitational name from any of several places called Harlaw in Midlothian, Peeblesshire, and Berwickshire, named in Older Scots with <i>hare</i> ‘gray’ + <i>law</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Herley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Art, Cormac.","Irish: variant of   Hurley  , probably via   Herlihy  .","English: variant of   Harley   or   Hurley  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Harley was born in 1120, in Harley, Shropshire, England, his father, John de Harley Sir, was 35 and his mother, Alice de Leighton \"de Harley\" Lady, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Katherine de Croft. He died in 1148, in England, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1120–1148":"1120–1148","1127–1148":"1127–1148","1148–1204":"1148–1204","1085–1120":"1085–1120","1095–1138":"1095–1138","1138":"1138","1204":"1204","1127":"1127","1148":"1148","Abt. 1138":"umbes 1138","1120":"1120","1085":"1085","Aft. 1120":"pärast 1120","1095":"1095","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1120–1148":"1120–1148","1127–1148":"1127–1148","1148–1204":"1148–1204","1085–1120":"1085–1120","1095–1138":"1095–1138","1138":"1138","1204":"1204","1127":"1127","1148":"1148","Abt. 1138":"noin 1138","1120":"1120","1085":"1085","Aft. 1120":"1120 jälkeen","1095":"1095","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1120–1148":"1120–1148","1127–1148":"1127–1148","1148–1204":"1148–1204","1085–1120":"1085–1120","1095–1138":"1095–1138","1138":"1138","1204":"1204","1127":"1127","1148":"1148","Abt. 1138":"environ 113